SIMPLE: establish
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Establish
<hw>Es*tab"lish</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Established</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Establishing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>establissen</ets>, OF. <ets>establir</ets>, F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧tablir</ets>, fr. L. <ets>stabilire</ets>, fr.
<ets>stabilis</ets> firm, steady, stable. See <er>Stable</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>, <er>-ish</er>, and cf. <er>Stablish</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To make stable or firm; to fix immovably or firmly; to
set (a thing) in a place and make it stable there; to settle; to
confirm.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So were the churches <qex>established</qex> in the faith.</q>
<rj><qau>Acts xvi. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The best <qex>established</qex> tempers can scarcely forbear being
borne down.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Confidence which must precede union could be
<qex>established</qex> only by consummate prudence and self-control.</q>
<rj><qau>Bancroft.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To appoint or constitute for permanence, as
officers, laws, regulations, etc.; to enact; to ordain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By the consent of all, we were <qex>established</qex>⟦br⟧
The people's magistrates.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now, O king, <qex>establish</qex> the decree, and sign the
writing, that it be not changed.</q> <rj><qau>Dan. vi. 8.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To originate and secure the permanent existence of;
to found; to institute; to create and regulate; -- said of a colony, a
state, or other institutions.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He hath <qex>established</qex> it [the earth], he created it not
in vain, he formed it to be inhabited.</q> <rj><qau>Is. xlv.
18.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Woe to him that buildeth a town with blood, and
<qex>establisheth</qex> a city by iniquity!</q> <rj><qau>Hab. ii.
12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To secure public recognition in favor of; to prove
and cause to be accepted as true; <as>as, to <ex>establish</ex> a fact,
usage, principle, opinion, doctrine, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At the mouth of two witnesses, or at the mouth of three witnesses,
shall the matter be <qex>established</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Deut. xix.
15.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To set up in business; to place advantageously in a
fixed condition; -- used reflexively; <as>as, he <ex>established</ex>
himself in a place; the enemy <ex>established</ex> themselves in the
citadel.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>established</ent>⟦br⟧
